    <h1>&#x2018;Roast&#x2019; marsh&#xAD;mal&#xAD;lows too</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201121/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-21"><time>2020-11-21</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>A mind-bog­gling range of ac­tiv­i­ties awaits visi­tors to Changi Fes­tive Vil­lage from now till year’s end, in­clud­ing fes­tive craft ses­sions, drone-fly­ing work­shops and ter­rar­ium and aquas­cape classes.</p>
    <p>But one of the high­lights is the snow­fall that is sched­uled twice ev­ery hour at the Shi­seido For­est Val­ley at ground level and the Canopy Park at</p>
    <p>Level 5.</p>
    <p>An­other fes­tive ac­tiv­ity to do is “roast­ing” marsh­mal­lows at an in­ter­ac­tive fire­place (above) at Shi­seido For­est Val­ley. Visi­tors need only show a min­i­mum of $30 spend­ing for two peo­ple to en­ter the For­est Val­ley to en­joy the dec­o­ra­tions and photo op­por­tu­ni­ties.</p>
    <p>An In­sta­gram-wor­thy stop along the fes­tive route in the Vil­lage is the 16m-tall Christ­mas tree, which is adorned with hun­dreds of sil­ver, gold and red stars, baubles and fairy lights.</p>
    <p>Put up over five con­sec­u­tive nights, in­clud­ing erect­ing the in­ter­nal steel struc­ture of the tree and the tun­nel un­der­neath it, the tree tow­ers over the other green­ery in the Shi­seido For­est Val­ley, pro­vid­ing a con­trast to the for­est’s usual green with its fes­tive and joy­ous dec­o­ra­tions.</p>

